^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The question was asked about super accept after a strong 1N opening - 15/17. I always play super accept with four card support unless I have the flattest 15 points NT opening. Marty Bergen is a strong proponent of this method. It is based on the Law of Total Tricks as you can bid to three level with nine card fit. However, that is not the mainstream. The mainstream requires nine card fit and 16/17 points. That is something that the Partnerships should discuss and agree on.|
PG| ***** 24 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|As far as the play is concerned Ann did fine. However,I have a few minor suggestions. With the diamond Queen opening you have no diamond loser, one possible club loser, one heart loser and two spade losers if everything goes wrong. You basically need one of four finesses to work to make the contract. As I mentioned I don't like to waste my trumps and would not ruff a diamond at trick three.|
PG| ***** 25 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|I would take a club finesse after winning the opening lead. Then I would lose the heart finesse. Eventually when I get back to the dummy I would lead the spade ten or a low spade to the seven. Following my way we make the same number of tricks but it is technically a better way.|
