^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|There is not much to talk about the play. The under-lead by Ally is a good play considering the holding in the dummy - a rare occasion for it to be correct. On the issue of 1NT forcing, a passed hand with limit raise value and 3 card support has no good bid. With Drury when you have a limit raise and 3-card support you query partner whether the opening was weak or strong.|
PG| ***** 42 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The more popular version of semi-forcing is that 1NT is semi-forcing by a passed hand. The idea here is, if opener has a minimum hand, since responder has already passed, there is little chance of game. So, with a 5-3-3-2 hand, rather than bidding a 3-card minor, opener can pass and play 1NT. However, the main issue is what happens if responder has a 3-card limit raise. There are 2 choices.|
PG| ***** 43 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|You can play Drury (in which, by a passed hand, 2C shows a 3-card limit raise and 2D shows a 4-card limit raise); that eliminates the possibility of the 1N bidder having a 3-card limit raise. Drury is favored by people who open light in 3rd and 4th seat.|
PG| ***** 44 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|As you can probably guess, since I am not a big fan of light openers, I am also not a fan of Drury. So, one solution is to still play 1N forcing rather than semi-forcing, even by a passed hand; I play that with many partners, and it work out just fine. |
PG| ***** 45 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The other choice, if you prefer 1NT semi-forcing, is to play that you cannot bid 1NT semi-forcing with a 3-card limit raise. You revert to SAYC, whereby you bid 2 of a minor to show 10-11 points. Therefore, you have to play that new suits  by responder are still forcing, even by an unpassed hand. Again, I usually play that way, and think it works out fine.|
PG| ***** 46 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|My basic philosophy of bidding is to keep things as simple as possible. So, I think there is merit to playing the same bids as forcing whether or not you are a passed hand. Also, I suggest that most less experienced partnerships, particularly if you are new to 2 over 1, should play 1NT forcing in all seats, rather than semi-forcing.|
